2026-03-19 20:46:10,790 [DEBUG] openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/embeddings', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-740dfbc0-ddc2-41c1-ab02-71b4dea0e7b3', 'post_parser': <function AsyncEmbeddings.create.<locals>.parser at 0x778c331830a0>, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'input': ['Low Energy Phonon Bursts Created By Fast Neutron Damage\n\nLow Energy Phonon Bursts Created By Fast Neutron Damage\nA. Armatol,1 C. Augier,1 L. Bergé,2 J. Billard,1 H.J. Birch,3 J. Blé,4 C.L. Chang,5, 6, 7 Y.-Y. Chang,8\n\nL. Chaplinsky,9 G. Cline,10 A. Cochard,2 I. Cojocari,2 J. Colas,1 M. De Jesus,1 P. de Marcillac,2 K. Dwinger,3\n\nR. Faure,1 S. Fiorucci,10 M. Garcia-Sciveres,10, 11 J. Gascon,1 C. Girard-Carillo,4 W. Guo,12, 13 L. Haegel,1\n\nS.J. Haselschwardt,14 S.A. Hertel,9 K. Hunter,15 L. Juigne,3 A. Juillar', ' S.A. Hertel,9 K. Hunter,15 L. Juigne,3 A. Juillard,1 A. Kavner,3 J. Lamblin,4 T. Le-Bellec,1\n\nX. Li,10 J. Lin,8, 10 R. Mahapatra,15 S. Marnieros,2 C. Marrache,2 N. Martini,1 W. Matava,8, 10 D.N. McKinsey,8, 10\n\nJ. Menu,4 K. Moraa,3 V. Novati,4 E. Olivieri,2 B. Penning,3 M. Platt,15 M. Pyle,8, 10 D. Poda,2 Y. Qi,12, 13\n\nM. Reed,8 R.K. Romani,8, a) I. Rydstrom,8 B. Sadoulet,8 S. Scorza,4 B. Serfass,8 P. Sorensen,10 S. Steinfeld,8, 10\n\nH. Su,9 A. Suzuki,10 R.L. Vaughn II,9 C. Veihmeyer,8 V. Velan,10 G. Wang,5', '. Vaughn II,9 C. Veihmeyer,8 V. Velan,10 G. Wang,5 P. Vittaz,1 Y. Wang,8, 10\n\nM.R. Williams,10, b) and J. Wuko9\n\n(TESSERACT Collaboration)\nK. E. J. Myers,16, 10 L. Bernstein,16, 10 M. Potts,17 and J. Orrell17\n\narXiv:2603.17964v1  [physics.ins-det]  18 Mar 2026\n\n1)Univ. Lyon, Université Lyon 1, CNRS/IN2P3, IP2I-Lyon, F-69622, Villeurbanne, France\n2)Université Paris-Saclay, CNRS/IN2P3, IJCLab, 91405 Orsay, France\n3)Department of Physics, University of Zurich, Winterthurerstrasse 190, 8057 Zurich,\nSwitzerland\n', 'Winterthurerstrasse 190, 8057 Zurich,\nSwitzerland\n4)Univ. Grenoble Alpes, CNRS, Grenoble INP, LPSC-IN2P3, 38000 Grenoble, France\n5)Argonne National Laboratory, 9700 S Cass Ave, Lemont, IL 60439, USA\n6)Kavli Institute for Cosmological Physics, The University of Chicago, 5640 S Ellis Ave., Chicago,\nIL 60637\n7)Department of Astronomy and Astrophysics, The University of Chicago, Eckhardt, 5640 S Ellis Ave., Chicago,\nIL 60637\n8)University of California Berkeley, Department of Physics, 366 LeConte Hall 7300, Berk', 'Department of Physics, 366 LeConte Hall 7300, Berkeley, CA 94720,\nUSA\n9)University of Massachusetts, Amherst Center for Fundamental Interactions and Department of Physics, 101 Stockbridge Hall,\n80 Campus Center Way, Amherst, MA 01003-9337 USA\n10)Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, 1 Cyclotron Rd., Berkeley, CA 94720, USA\n11)International Center for Quantum-field Measurement Systems for Studies of the Universe and Particles (QUP,\nWPI), High Energy Accelerator Research Organization (KEK), Oho 1-1, Tsukuba,', 'tor Research Organization (KEK), Oho 1-1, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0801,\nJapan\n12)Department of Mechanical Engineering, FAMU-FSU College of Engineering, Florida State University, 2525 Pottsdamer Street,\nTallahassee, FL 32310, USA\n13)National High Magnetic Field Laboratory, 1800 E Paul Dirac Dr., Tallahassee, FL 32310,\nUSA\n14)University of Michigan, Randall Laboratory of Physics, Ann Arbor, MI 48109-1040,\nUSA\n15)Texas A&M University, Department of Physics and Astronomy, 4242 TAMU, 578 University Dr., College Sta', 'ronomy, 4242 TAMU, 578 University Dr., College Station, TX 77843-4242,\nUSA\n16)University of California Berkeley, Department of Nuclear Engineering, Berkeley, CA 94720,\nUSA\n17)Pacific Northwest National Lab, 902 Battelle Boulevard, Richland, WA 99354, USA\n\n(Dated: 19 March 2026)\n\nSolid state athermal phonon calorimeters used in the search for low mass dark matter or coherent neutrino-nucleus\ninteractions have long observed a large excess of events below several hundred eV. The relaxation of damage created\nby', 'al hundred eV. The relaxation of damage created\nby the interaction of fast cosmic ray neutrons with the detector has been proposed as a source of these excess events.\nBy comparing neutron exposed detectors to control detectors, we report the first measurement of phonon bursts caused\nby damage created by fast neutrons. Differences in the spectral shape, the rate dependence on thermal history, and the\nobserved spectral rate scaled to the neutron exposure between irradiated and control detectors suggest that o', 'en irradiated and control detectors suggest that our observed\nLEE backgrounds are not dominated by neutron damage-induced phonon bursts.\n\nI.\nINTRODUCTION\n\nDetecting rare, low-energy nuclear recoils, such as those\ncreated by low mass dark matter or coherent neutrino-nucleus\ninteractions, remains one of the most challenging problems in\nmodern detector development1–5. Cryogenic solid state de-\ntectors have achieved eV-scale thresholds capable of probing\nnew parameter space for low-mass dark matter2,6,7, but ha', 'ameter space for low-mass dark matter2,6,7, but have\nbeen limited by a high rate of poorly understood non-ionizing\n\na)Corresponding author: rkromani@berkeley.edu; These authors contributed\nequally to this work; now at: National Institute of Standards and Technology,\nApplied Physics Division, 325 Broadway, Boulder, CO 80305, USA\nb)Corresponding author:\nmichaelwilliams@lbl.gov; These authors con-\ntributed equally to this work.\n\n\nLow Energy Phonon Bursts Created By Fast Neutron Damage\n2\n\nposed as a control. Th', 'd By Fast Neutron Damage\n2\n\nposed as a control. These detectors use Transition Edge Sen-\nsors (TESs)16 coupled to aluminum phonon collection fins\nin the common Quasiparticle-trap-assisted Electrothermal-\nfeedback Transition-edge-sensor (QET)17 configuration. The\ncontrol/irradiated pair was run simultaneously in a single op-\ntical cavity which was shielded from infrared radiation and\nelectromagnetic interference and operated in a dilution refrig-\nerator in a subbasement of the University of California, Berke', 'subbasement of the University of California, Berke-\nley physics department. The TESs were read out with single\nstage DC SQUID arrays.\nThe first set of detectors (set A) were an unmodified ver-\nsion of the detectors in Refs.2,6,7. The second set of detec-\ntors (set B) were based on a modified version of the detectors\nin Refs.2,6,7, where the fin length was reduced by a factor of\napproximately two and the number of QETs and TES length\nwere increased by approximately a factor of four. The re-\nsulting detector ', 'mately a factor of four. The re-\nsulting detector had a very similar aluminum coverage (and\nphonon dynamics) to the detectors in Refs.2,6,7, while the\nlonger TESs increased the quiescent bias power and saturation\nenergy of the detector by approximately four times. All detec-\ntors were manufactured on the same wafer as the 1 mm detec-\ntor in Ref.7, and were suspended by wire bonds11. We used\ntwo phonon readout channels per detector to separate “shared”\n(phonon-coupled) from “singles” (film-coupled) LEE6.\n\nCo', 'n-coupled) from “singles” (film-coupled) LEE6.\n\nCosmic Ray\nAir Shower\n\nControl Detector\n\nDetector Crystal\n\nNeutron Source\n\nTungsten TES\n\nAluminum Fins\nNeutron Irradiated \n\nDetector\n\nNeutrons\n\nDisplaced Atoms\nPhonons\n\nNeutron Scattering\nDamage Creation\nDefect Relaxation\n\nFIG. 1.\nDiagrams showing the proposed neutron damage and re-\nlaxation process. (Left) Fast neutrons recoil off individual atoms in\nthe detector crystal. (Center Bottom) The energetic “primary knock-\non atom” ricochets through the detector cr', ' knock-\non atom” ricochets through the detector crystal, impacting additional\natoms, creating extended defects. As atoms are displaced from the\nregular crystal lattice, this defect constitutes a metastable energetic\nstate. (Right Bottom) After creation, the defect relaxes into a lower\nenergy configuration, emitting athermal phonons. (Right Top) Pho-\ntograph of the detectors, mounted next to each other in the cryogenic\npackage. In each of the sub-diagrams, the tungsten TES films are\nmarked in pink, while the', 'e tungsten TES films are\nmarked in pink, while the aluminum films are marked in green.\n\nB.\nNeutron Exposures\n\nlow background events1,2,8.\nWhile a number of mechanisms for this so-called “Low En-\nergy Excess” (LEE) have been proposed and experimentally\nobserved (including high energy particles causing scintilla-\ntion in insulating materials around the detector9, stress asso-\nciated with detector mounting10,11, and events originating in\naluminum structures on the detector surface6,11,12), the most\nproblematic', 'the detector surface6,11,12), the most\nproblematic background remains unexplained, but seems to\noriginate from within the bulk crystal forming the phonon de-\ntector’s target7.\nA mechanism for creating LEE in the detector substrate was\nrecently proposed in Ref.13, where the authors posit that fast\nneutrons from e.g. cosmic rays secondaries (CRs) will inter-\nact with the detector substrate, creating damage in the crystal\nstructure which relaxes over long time scales. The relaxation\nof such damage would create', 'scales. The relaxation\nof such damage would create bursts of phonons originating\nin the substrate and scaling with its volume, consistent with\nobservations7. Similar phenomena have also been described\nand studied through simulation focused on other contexts as\nshown in Refs.14,15. This letter describes an attempt to probe\nthis proposed damage hypothesis.\n\nThe irradiated (“rad”) detector in set A was exposed to both\n2.45 MeV neutrons from a Deuterium-Deuterium (DD) gener-\nator for 5.8 days and 0-11 MeV neutr', 'm (DD) gener-\nator for 5.8 days and 0-11 MeV neutrons from an Americium-\nBeryllium (AmBe) source for 24 hours, while the irradi-\nated detector in set B was exposed only to DD neutrons for\n4.8 days. Both detectors were exposed before mounting, and\nwere located as close to the neutron sources as mechanically\npossible. The control detectors were not exposed to artificial\nneutron sources, but were unavoidably exposed to the same\nbackground neutron sources (e.g. cosmic ray secondaries) as\nour irradiated detector', 'cosmic ray secondaries) as\nour irradiated detectors. We expect that these artificial neu-\ntron exposures should negligibly activate our detectors (see\nappendix A), and that any resulting radioactive decays should\ncontribute only high energy (keV+) events, far outside of our\nLEE region of interest. Methods for estimating the neutron-\ninduced damage can be found in appendix B, and the expo-\nsures in table I.\n\nC.\nOperation and Data Processing\n\nII.\nMETHODS\n\nWe cooled our detectors to millikelvin temperatures in', 'ooled our detectors to millikelvin temperatures in a\ndilution refrigerator within several days of irradiation and be-\ngan periodically recording 2 to 12 hour datasets to measure\nthe LEE spectrum as a function of time since cooldown. Ev-\nery 30 minutes of data-taking, we performed an IV sweep, a\n∂I/∂V measurement at the TES operating point and a photon\ncalibration to characterize the state of each channel and to ac-\ncount for drifts in response over time6,7. Approximately two\nmonths after the initial cooldow', 'Approximately two\nmonths after the initial cooldown (Run 1) of the Set A detec-\n\nA.\nDetectors\n\nTo test if damage to the substrate lattice from fast neutrons\ncan create LEE-like events, we compare LEE observations in\ntwo sets of two identically fabricated 1 mm thick by 1 cm2\n\nsilicon athermal phonon detectors, one of which was exposed\nto a large fast neutron flux, while the other was kept unex-\n\n\nLow Energy Phonon Bursts Created By Fast Neutron Damage\n3\n\n10\n1\n\ntors, we cooled them down a second time (Run 2) ', '\n\ntors, we cooled them down a second time (Run 2) to monitor\nthe evolution of their backgrounds over time.\nAfter taking data, we characterized our detectors’ Cross\nSpectral Density (CSD) and modeled their frequency depen-\ndent responsivity dP/dI(ω) by measuring their IV and ∂I/∂V\nresponses. We determined the time domain current template\nfor phonon pulses using the measured phonon response from\nphoton calibrations6,7.\nUsing these phonon templates and\nCSDs, we constructed a two-channel, one-amplitude optimal\n', ' constructed a two-channel, one-amplitude optimal\nfilter used as an offline software trigger and to measure the\nenergy of phonon events2,7.\nIn each detector, we observed intermittent mechanically ex-\ncitable noise at ~200 Hz, which we interpret as a vibration\nmode of the wire bonds used to mechanically support the de-\ntectors. In some detectors, during periods of high environmen-\ntal vibration excitation, we observed many low (≲10 eV) en-\nergy phonon events occurring in phase with the noise. To re-\nmove per', 'occurring in phase with the noise. To re-\nmove periods with these events (which are unassociated with\nthe higher energy neutron damage induced phonon bursts we\nare interested in studying), we measured the average current\nthrough our TESs in a roughly 200 ms long pre-pulse region,\nand remove from the analysis (“cut”) events for which this\ncurrent exceeded a set threshold. Details can be found in ap-\npendix C.\nAdditionally, we observed background events that were co-\nincident between the two detectors, seemin', 'ere co-\nincident between the two detectors, seemingly caused by scin-\ntillation of our PCB, electromagnetic interference, and possi-\nbly additional effects. To remove these events (which are also\nunassociated with the primary LEE effect we wish to study\nhere), we cut events where there is an event in the other de-\ntector within 50 µs of the main event trigger (see appendix\nD).\nAs in Refs.2,6,7, we applied a δχ2 based cut designed to\ndiscriminate “singles” from “shared” events. We also impose\nstandard data q', 'om “shared” events. We also impose\nstandard data quality cuts as in Refs.2,6,7 which we further dis-\ncuss in appendix E. We inject simulated waveforms at known\nrate and energy to estimate the passage fraction for each cut\n(see appendix F).\n\nSet A\nRun 1\n\nSet B\n\nControl\nRef. 7\n1 mm\n\n10\n3\n\nEvents/(eV g s)\n\nEvents/(eV g s)\n\nAmBe\n+DD\n\n10\n2\n\nDD\n\n10\n4\n\n10\n3\n\nControl\nRef. 7\nCPDv2\n\n10\n5\n\n0\n20\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n50\n100\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\nFIG. 2. (Left) Set A spectra, measured approximately 6 hours after\ncooldo', 'ectra, measured approximately 6 hours after\ncooldown. Yellow corresponds to a detector irradiated with fast neu-\ntrons from AmBe and DD sources (see text), while blue corresponds\nto the control (unexposed) detector. For comparison, purple shows\nthe spectrum on day 3.4 in the 1 mm detector in Ref.7. (Right) Spec-\ntra measured for the detectors in set B, measured approximately 1.1\ndays after cooldown. Red corresponds to the detector exposed to DD\nneutrons (see text), green is control, and light blue is the “C', ' text), green is control, and light blue is the “CPDv2”\ndetector spectrum shown in Ref.7.\n\nSet A Run 1 AmBe+DD\nSet A Run 2 AmBe+DD\nSet B DD\n\nRate from 15 to 30 eV (events/g s)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n2\n\nSet A Run 1 Control\nSet A Run 2 Control\nSet B Control\n\n10\n3\n\n100\n101\n\nDay in Run\n\nFIG. 3.\nRate of events between 15 and 30 eV (where neutron-\ninduced excess events dominate) observed in the detectors in sets A\nand B. Irradiated detectors are shown in bright colors with crosses,\ncontrol detectors are shown in dark colors w', 'sses,\ncontrol detectors are shown in dark colors with dots. Dashed lines\nshow fits to Eqn. 1, with 1 sigma uncertainties shaded. Dotted lines\nare fits with the power law exponent fixed (Eqn. 3).\n\nIII.\nRESULTS\n\nIn both detector sets, we independently observed a signif-\nicant excess of events above roughly 10 eV in the irradiated\ndetectors compared to the non-irradiated detectors (see Fig.\n2). A larger excess was observed in set A, which we expect to\nhave more neutron-induced damage (see table I).\nIn the set ', ' neutron-induced damage (see table I).\nIn the set A detectors, the spectral shape of the excess\nevents observed in the irradiated detector was significantly\ndifferent than the control spectra. Specifically, we observe\na Gaussian peak in the irradiated device spectrum centered\naround 20.1 ± 0.1 eV with a width of 4.4 ± 0.1 eV on top of\nthe standard LEE background, with a tail towards higher ener-\ngies. The measured detector resolution is significantly better\nthan this width (see appendix I), indicating that ', 'than this width (see appendix I), indicating that the measured\nwidth is due to a physical process rather than a monoenergetic\npeak broadened by detector response. This peak is larger than\nthe Frenkel pair formation energy18,19and thus suggests the\n\nrelaxation of more complex defect states. In the set B irradi-\nated detector, which has a higher dynamic range but roughly\n3 times less exposure to neutrons, we do not see a clear peak,\nbut instead a more uniformly enhanced background.\nIn both the irradiated and '], 'model': 'qwen3-embedding-0.6b', 'encoding_format': 'base64'}}
