d\nevent shape, leading us to hypothesize that EMI may be responsible\nfor these events.\n\nFIG. 11. “Coincident” event with a phonon-like pulse shape. Light\nlines are the raw waveforms, and dark lines are filtered with a 20\nkHz low pass filter for clarity. Green and red (blue and orange) are\nthe left and right channels of the control (irradiated) detector. We\nhypothesize that these events are caused by our PCB scintillating (see\ntext).\n\nEnergy Absorbed in Right TES (eV),\n\n20\n\nno signal', '\nEnergy Absorbed in Right TES (eV),\n\n20\n\nno signal.\n\nPhonon Pulse Shape\n\n15\n\nSupplementary Materials Section E: Data Quality Cuts\n\n10\n\nIn addition to the coincident event and vibration induced\nevent cuts, we employ two additional cuts to ensure that the\nevents accepted into the final analysis are consistent with\nphonon-coupled LEE events.\n\n5\n\nFirst, we apply a low frequency χ2 cut, which compares the\nobserved shape of the events to a phonon event template, con-\nsidering only frequencies below 50 kHz, where ', 'on-\nsidering only frequencies below 50 kHz, where signal domi-\nnates. This cut removes events for which this low frequency\nχ2 exceeds an amplitude dependent threshold, i.e. which are\nnot shaped like phonon events. While other cuts successfully\nremove the vast majority of events which would fail this low\nfrequency χ2 cut, the cut does remove a small number of un-\nusually shaped pulses, possibly induced by EMI (see Fig. 12).\n\n0\n\n0\n5\n10\n15\n20\nEnergy Absorbed in Left TES (eV),\n\nPhonon Pulse Shape\n\nFIG. 13. Scat', ' Left TES (eV),\n\nPhonon Pulse Shape\n\nFIG. 13. Scatter plot of triggered events in the control detector in the\nsecond run of the set A detectors, showing energy absorbed in the left\nvs. right TES, assuming a phonon pulse shape. Events passing the\nδχ2 based single/shared cut (i.e. shared/phonon events) are shown\nin pink, while events failing the cut (i.e. singles) are shown in blue.\nNote that our trigger threshold in this work is somewhat higher than\nin previous publications.\n\nFinally, we apply a δχ2 based cu', 'us publications.\n\nFinally, we apply a δχ2 based cut to remove “single”\nevents6,35 (i.e. those occurring within the aluminum fins of\nour detector6 rather than within the substrate), identically to\nas described in Refs.2,6,7.\nIn short, we find the difference\nbetween the χ2 from fitting two-channel, single-amplitude\ntemplates to both channels of a single detector using either\na phonon template or a “singles” template (in which a sin-\ngle faster pulse occurs in one channel, with essentially no re-\nsponse in the', 'one channel, with essentially no re-\nsponse in the other). Through making these comparisons, we\ncan determine if an event is more “phonon-like” or “singles-\nlike,” considering both the pulse shape and relative response\nin each channel.\n\nSupplementary Materials Section F: Cut Passage Efficiency\n\nThe acceptance of the above quality cuts is measured at a\nrange of energies: 0 eV, 15 eV, 20 eV, and 25 eV as these\nsampled the region of interest in this work, and it allows us\nto confirm the acceptance has no energ', 't allows us\nto confirm the acceptance has no energy dependence. The ac-\n\n\nLow Energy Phonon Bursts Created By Fast Neutron Damage\n13\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nceptance at 0 eV is measured via a population of randomly\nsampled events when the cuts are applied. These events, be-\ning random in nature, will consist of a largely quiescent base-\nline and its fluctuations and are unlikely to have real phonon\nevents. However, given that the rate of events is non-zero,\nthere is still some probability that a random selection has a', 'ill some probability that a random selection has a\npulse in it, but given the rate is low, the large majority of these\nevents will have a maximum reconstructed event amplitude\nGaussian distributed around zero with the σ of the distribution\ngiven by the detector resolution. To measure the cut accep-\ntance, we take the ratio of events cut from these samples to the\ntotal number of events. The acceptance at energies above 0 eV\nis done via "salting". Here, we inject fake signals into the data\nstream at a known r', 'ect fake signals into the data\nstream at a known rate and energy and measure the passage\nfraction just like the randomly selected events. Though these\nevents have non-zero energy, they are randomly distributed in\ntime just as the randomly selected events. More information\non the salting algorithm used can be found in2. The passage\nefficiency of the various cuts described in D,C, and E can be\nfound below in tables V,VI, and VII.\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 0.2\n\nDay 0.8\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)', ' 0.8\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 2.8\n\nDay 4.3\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 6.7\n\nDay 9.6\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 12.9\n\nDay 13.7\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n40\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 25.7\n\nDay ', ' (eV)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 25.7\n\nDay 26.8\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 30.3\n\nDay 32.7\n\nSupplementary Materials Section G: Complete Spectra\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\nPhonon Energy (eV)\n\nIn the main text, for the sake of brevity we only show two\nrepresentative spectra. In Figs. 14, 15, 16, and 17 we show\nspectra of all the datasets taken as part of this study.\n\n10\n1\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\nDay 3