\nbe consistent between the irradiated and control detectors and\nwith the fit α parameters before the warm-up period. In c', 'e fit α parameters before the warm-up period. In con-\ntrast to the pre-warm-up period, the post-warm-up prefactors\nβ appeared to be similar, with the irradiated detector’s pref-\n\nRp(t) = βt−α\n(H1)\nRwu(t) = β(t −twu)−α\n(H2)\nR f (t) = βt−αrad\n(H3)\n\nIn the first run of the set A detectors, we fit the third through\neighth data point in the pre-warm up period with the two-\nparameter Rp(t) model. The first two data points appear to\nfollow a different trend, which we were unable to satisfacto-\nrily fit by introduc', 'we were unable to satisfacto-\nrily fit by introducing a variable start time for the power law\n(i.e. fitting to R(t) = β(t −t0)−α). Certainly, a more com-\nplicated model involving e.g. multiple power law terms (e.g.\nR(t) = β1t−α1 +β2t−α2) could fit these early data points, how-\never, adding more free parameters to the model seems to fail\nto provide much explanatory power. Similarly, for the second\nrun of the set A detectors, we drop the first point from these\nfits, as it appears to be systematically higher. ', '\nfits, as it appears to be systematically higher. Although they\nbroadly seem consistent with the same power law constant, the\nSet B detectors were only measured at three points in time, too\n\n\nLow Energy Phonon Bursts Created By Fast Neutron Damage\n14\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nSee table X for fit parameters.\n\nDay 1.9\n\nDay 3.9\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\n10\n2\n\n10\n2\n\nRf (t) = βt−αrad\n(H4)\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n4\n\n10\n4\n\nSupplementary Materials Section I: Detector Resolutions\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n\n0\n10\n20\n30\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nDay 6.4\n\nDay 8.9\n\nAs we prev', '10\n20\n30\n\n10\n1\n\n10\n1\n\nDay 6.4\n\nDay 8.9\n\nAs we previously described7, the energy resolutions of our\ndetectors are limited by phonon shot noise which decreases in\n\nRate (eV g s)\n1\n\n10\n2\n\n10\n2\n\n10\n3\n\n10\n3\n\n