d by the VEVs of η1,2. This leads to the residual discrete symmetry NP , such\n\nas NP = (−1)\nkN\n\nδ , where k is integer. The subsequent breaking step breaks the electroweak\n\nsymmetry as well as NP , derived by the usual Higgs field. This leads to the final residual\n\ndiscrete symmetry, DP = (−1)\nkD\n\nδ , where D = T3 + N. The form of DP exists as a mixture\n\nof the weak isospin and the hyperdark, implying that the dark charge is nonabelian, as\n\nmentione', 'g that the dark charge is nonabelian, as\n\nmentioned. Notice that the half-integer U(1)N charge of the Higgs doublet implies that the\n\nweak vacuum conserves dark charge.\n\nWe assume that δ = p/m, where m and p are integers. After the breaking of the gauge\n\nsymmetry, the residual symmetry is a discrete cyclic group Zk. This implies that all matter\n\nfields must satisfy k πD\n\nδ\n= ni2π with D = Du, Dd, De, DH+, Dν corespond to i = 1, ..., 5 and\n\nni’s are an integer number. This condition leads to:\n\n−5\n\n3 + 2m\n\n3p', 'r number. This condition leads to:\n\n−5\n\n3 + 2m\n\n3p = 2n1\n\nk ,\n−m + 5p\n\n3p\n= 2n2\n\nk ,\n\n5 −m\n\np = 2n3\n\nk ,\nm\n\np = 2n4\n\nk ,\n2n5\n\nk\n= 5.\n(1)\n\n\n6\n\nSolving the system yields:\n\nm = 2(n1 −n2)p\n\nk\n,\nk = −2\n\n5 (n1 + 2n2) ,\n\nn3 = −2n1 −n2,\nn4 = n1 −n2,\nn5 = 5\n\n2k.\n(2)\n\nThis implies that k is even.\nHence, the residual symmetry DP is determined to be an\n\neven cyclic group. The smallest group of which is with k = 2, obtained by a dark parity\n\np D = (−1)\n1\n2 (5+3n1)D. We multiply the dark parity P with the spin parity S =', 'ultiply the dark parity P with the spin parity S =\n\nP = (−1)\nm\n\n(−1)2s, which is always conserved, to redefine the residual symmetry conveniently DP =\n\nZ2 = {1, PS}. In short, the theory is governed by a dark parity, such that\n\nDP ≡PS = (−1)\n1\n2 (5+3n1)D+2s,\n(3)\n\nwhere D and s are dark charge and spin, respectively.\n\nRemarks are in order:\n\n• If n1 = 4m + 1, then all SM particles and new particles νaR, N1,2, η1,2 are even under\n\nZ2, whereas the particles S1,2,3, φ1,2,3 are odd.\n\n• If n1 = 4m + 3, then up-typ', ',3, φ1,2,3 are odd.\n\n• If n1 = 4m + 3, then up-type components of doublets and singlets νaR, N1,2, η1,2 are\n\neven under Z2, whereas down-type components of doublets and singlets S1,2,3, φ1,2,3\n\nare odd.\n\n• If n1 = 4m or 4m + 2, then some physical fields cannot be any eigenstate of the\n\nZ2 symmetry defined by the generator DP = (−1)\n1\n2 (5+3n1)D+2s. Hence, the residual\n\nsymmetry must be larger than the present Z2.\n\nSo among the minimal choices of the residual symmetry, we will take the case n1 = 4m + 1\n\ninto', ' symmetry, we will take the case n1 = 4m + 1\n\ninto account. Interestingly, this residual symmetry plays the crucial roles, ensuring both the\n\nstability of dark matter candidates and the radiative origin of the inverse seesaw responsible\n\nfor small neutrino masses. It is noteworthy that the scalar singlets φ1, φ2 and φ3 do not\n\nacquire any VEV as they carry non-trivial dark charges protected by the dark parity DP .\n\nThis symmetry is also essential to forbid tree-level mass terms, which otherwise mix the\n\neve', 'ree-level mass terms, which otherwise mix the\n\neven fields N1,2, νaR with the odd fields S1,2,3. Such odd fermions would generate effective\n\nMajorana mass terms like ¯Nc\n1N1 and ¯Nc\n2N2 leading to the realization of the radiative inverse\n\nseesaw.\n\n\n7\n\nIII.\nNEUTRINO MASS GENERATION AND DARK MATTER STABILITY\n\nFrom the particle representation content under the previously described relevant symme-\n\ntries, we can build the following Yukawa interactions for charged fermions:\n\nLc.f.\nY ukawa = he\nab ¯LaLϕebR + hd\na', 'd fermions:\n\nLc.f.\nY ukawa = he\nab ¯LaLϕebR + hd\nab ¯QaLϕdbR + hu\nab ¯QaL ˜ϕubR + H.c.,\n(4)\n\nwhile the Yukawa interactions for neutral fermions are given by\n\nLn.f.\nY ukawa = hν\nab ¯LaL ˜ϕνbR + fν\na1¯νc\naRη1N1 + fν\na2¯νc\naRη2N2 + fN\n1 ¯Sc\n1N1φ1 + fN\n2 ¯Sc\n